attributes.description: The 95th percentile for the time screens take to execute, compared with one day prior. The 95th percentile says that 95% of the time screen duration is below that value, and 5% of the time it's above that value. A value under 2000 milliseconds for the 95th percentile is therefore indicative of very good performance.
attributes.title: [OS] Mobile/Reactive Screen 95th percentile duration

attributes.description: A map of average request duration, per application. attributes.description: A breakdown of the total duration of requests (overall) into the time spent on client side processing (load), network and server side processing, including the server side breakdown into the time spent on session acquisition, extensions, integrations and queries. For mobile & reactive web applications, load time on the client and network time are not available. This visualization can be used to help understand where are requests spending most of their time.
attributes.title: [OS] Request duration breakdown overall

attributes.description: Breakdown of requests into their number of extension, integration and query executions, plotted over time. Also shows the request volume itself and the volume of errors. This visualization can be used to help understand what is the bulk of activities done in the requests.
attributes.title: [OS] Request activities volume over time

attributes.description: Breakdown of the 95th percentile of request duration, into the time spent executing major request activities (load time on the client, server time, SAT, extension time, integration time, query time). For mobile & reactive web applications, load time on the client is not available, and total time is equal to server time. The 95th percentile says that 95% of the time duration is below that value, and 5% of the time it's above that value. This visualization can be used to help understand what request activities are impacting the most on request performance.
attributes.title: [OS] Request duration breakdown by activities over time

attributes.description: This is the main dashboard. Start from here and you will be able to drill down on to the more detailed dashboards.
attributes.title: [OS] Main

attributes.description: A count of the number of screens executed so far, compared with one day prior.
attributes.title: [OS] Screen count

attributes.description: The average time screens take to execute, compared with one day prior. This visualization can be used to have a ballpark idea of the duration of screens, and how it compares with the day before.
attributes.title: [OS] Screen average duration

attributes.description: The 95th percentile for the time screens take to execute, compared with one day prior. The 95th percentile says that 95% of the time screen duration is below that value, and 5% of the time it's above that value. A value under 2000 milliseconds for the 95th percentile is therefore indicative of very good performance.
attributes.title: [OS] Screen 95th percentile duration

attributes.description: Top 10 most executed screens, amongst all screens identified as slow, ordered by number of executions. This visualization can be used to help us understand what are the most problematic screens.
attributes.title: [OS] Top 10 most executed SLOW screens

attributes.description: Top 10 most executed screens. This visualization can be used to help us realize if applications are behaving as expected.
attributes.title: [OS] Top 10 most executed screens

attributes.description: Top 10 most executed screens, amongst all screens identified as slow, ordered by number of executions, plus the information of the 95th percentile of their duration. This visualization can be used to help us understand what are the most problematic screens.
attributes.title: [OS] Top 10 most executed SLOW screens (with 95th percentile duration)

attributes.description: The average duration that timers take to execute, compared with one day prior. This visualization can be used to have a ballpark idea of the duration of batch jobs and timers, and how it compares with the day before. Values are given in seconds, so null or 0 values should be understood as durations of less than 1 second in length.
attributes.title: [OS] Timer average duration

attributes.description: The 95th percentile for the duration that timers take to execute, compared with one day prior. The 95th percentile says that 95% of the timer duration is below that value, and 5% of the time it's above that value. A value under 200 milliseconds for the 95th percentile is therefore indicative of very good performance. Null or 0 value means that timers took less than 1 second to run.
attributes.title: [OS] Timer 95th percentile duration
